<br>
Let's say mob X takes 50 people to kill for an open raid and has a random spawn time of 7 days.  Mob X spawns, CasualGuildAlliance learns of this at the same time that UberGuild does.  CasualGuildAlliance can't get enough people together, UberGuild gets the mob anyways.<br>
<br>
Now, without random spawn times..<br>
<br>
Mob D spawns after a patch in the same zone as Mob N, TGuild and SGuild both want D, but TGuild also wants N.  SGuild decides that they are going to put in the commitment to take down D, TGuild is faced with a decision of killing D or N, they choose N because there are more loots.  Both TGuild and SGuild get what they want.<br>
<br>
Well, that's just the way I see it.. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulistero001.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Listero001</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(2/4/02 3:44:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1641.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Death of EQ's Casual-Raid Playerbase</span><hr size=1> In reply to Errtai's post, rhag one could EASILY be killed by an open &quot;raid&quot;.(yes, he's that easy)  Vind and statue could also be done with enough effort, I believe truk's open vind raid almost succeded.  Even Dozekar is doable with &quot;casual gamers&quot;, though he'd probably never be up to try.  Ct is a bit tough though.<br>
