/shrug <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uchodeberg1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chodeberg1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>w4nn4b3!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(2/4/02 4:10:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1641.topic&index=27>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Death of EQ's Casual-Raid Playerbase</span><hr size=1> EQ is full of content for both casual players and powergamers.  Powergamers will frequently be challenged by high end mobs that most of the eq population will never have an opportunity to see.  In order to defeat these mobs, the powergamers will acquire items that the casual player will probably never own.  There is nothing wrong with reward for time and effort invested in eq.<br>
<br>
Casual gamers can do quests, camp named spawns, crawl Kunark dungeons (Seb, KC, etc.) to fight the likes of Trak or VS, and maybe some Velious and Luclin dungeons as well.  Casual gamers will not be pushing the envelope on uber mob strats.  Why?  Because it takes time, and a lot of it, to figure that shit out.  If you define yourself as a casual gamer, then accept that as your fate in eq.  <br>
<br>
True, you pay your $10 a month and feel that you should have the same access to the Tormax's and Dain's of Norrath, but the fact remains that everyone that pays doesn't get to fight these mobs.  For one thing, saturating the market with uber items by decreasing the spawn time on these mobs will make eq the most boring game ever.  It would be like using gameshark or some shit to make every encounter trivial.  Secondly, the powergamers of EQ need something to keep us interested.  Let's just say that it isn't gratifying to kill a mob that everyone and their retarded dog can kill.  <br>
<br>
If you want to be able to experience everything in a game, maybe you should stick to console games, so there isn't 2000 people simultaneously trying to thwart your plans in EQ.  I just find it sad to see people complaining about a game that has so much content, that nobody will ever be able to acquire everything.  Maybe you need to realize that your desires are somewhat selfish and set reasonable goals for yourself and your friends.<br>
<br>
Just remember that EQ is a game, and if it is no longer fun for you, or you feel cheated in some way, then perhaps you should move on.  I'm not trying to be an ass, but that's just common sense.  The people who made this game don't care about YOUR opinion.  They are trying to please thousands of people at the same time.  Everyone is going to have their issues with the game, some conflicting, so VI has to do it's best to try to reach a happy medium for all players.  That is am impossible task imo, but Verant must be doing an ok job, because a lot of people still play.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I'm hardly a VI fanboy.  There's a lot of things that frustrate me about EQ, but they are greatly outweighed by the things that keep me interested and entertained.  I guess you should just ask yourself what keeps you here, and decide if it's worth it.  <br>
<br>
Chodeller<br>
60 Wizard<br>
Fallen Legacy<br>
